In the division of the provinces, Augustus provided for his own power, and for the dignity of the republic- The proconsuls of the senate, particularly those of Asia, Greece, and Africa, enjoyed a more honourable character than the lieute⁴ nants of the emperor, who commanded in Gaul or Syria. The former were attended by lictors, the latter by soldiers. A law was passed, that wherever the emperor was present, his extraordinary commiffion should supersede the ordinary jurisdiction of the governor, a custom was introduced, that the new conquesta belonged to the Imperial portion, and it'was soon discovered, that the authority of the Prince, the favourite epithet of Augustus, was -the same in every part of the empire.

In' return for this imaginary conceffion, Augustus obtained an important privilege, which rendered him master of Rome and Italy. By a dangerous exception to the ancient maxims, he was authorized to preserve his military command, supported by a numerous body of guards‚ even in time of peace, and in the heart of the capital. His command, indeed, was confined to those eiti- zens who were engaged in the service by the military oath3 but

such was the propensity of the Romans to servitude, that the oath was voluntarily taken by the magistrates, the senators, and the equestrian order, till the homage of fiattery was insensibly converted into an annual and solemn protestation of fidelity.

Although Augustus considered a military force, as the firmest foundation, he wisely rejected it, as a very odious instrument, of government.
